This instruction applies to Class 2 adsorbed gases, UN 3512 to UN 3526 on passenger aircraft and/or Cargo Aircraft only, as applicable. 

For cylinders, the general packing requirements of 5.0.2 and 5.2.0 must be met. 

Cylinders contructed as specified in 6.4 and in accordance with ISO 11513:2011 or ISO 9809-1:2010 are permitted for the transport of adsorbed gases provided that: 

		 101. The pressure of each filled cylinder must be less than 101.3 kPa at 20oC and less than 300 kPa at 50oC; 
 		 102. The minimum test pressure of the cylinder is 21 bar; 
 		 103. The minimum burst pressure of the cylinders is 94.5 bar; 
 		 104. The internal pressure at 65oC of the filled cylinder must no exceed the test pressure of the cylinder; 
 		 105. The adsorbent material must be compatible with the cylinder and must not form harmful or dangerous compounds with the gas to be adsorbed. The gas in combination with the adsorbent material must not affect or weaken the cylinder or cause a dangerous reaction (e.g. a catalyzing reaction); 
 		 106. The quality of the adsorbent must be verified at the time of each fill to assure the pressure and chemical stability requirements of this packing instruction are met each time an adsorbed gas package is offered for transport; 
 		 107. The adsorbent material must not meet the criteria of any of the classes or divisions in these Regulations; 
 		 108. The filling procedure must be in accordance with Annex A of ISO 11513:2011; 
 		 109. The maximum period for periodic inspections is five years; 
 		 110. The construction materials of the cylinders and their accessories must be compatible with the contents and must not react to form harmful or dangerous compounds therewith.
